  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear to come from legitimate sources. This is typically done by transferring the money through complex transactions to obscure its origin.\n\nIn China, the legal framework against money laundering is robust. The country has enacted specific laws and regulations to combat this illegal activity, such as the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China. Financial institutions and other entities are required to implement stringent measures to prevent money laundering, including customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions to the authorities.\n\nThe Chinese government also collaborates with international organizations and other countries to combat cross-border money laundering activities, reflecting its commitment to maintaining the integrity of the financial system and upholding the rule of law.",
